{{italic title}} '''''Would It Kill You To Stop Doing That?''''' is a 2012 non-fiction book by the American humorist [[Henry Alford (writer)|Henry Alford]] that details [[manners]] from around the world.
After being interested in a quote by [[Edmund Burke]] about how important manners are, Alford traveled around the world researching manners. He also interviews people such as etiquette authority [[Judith Martin]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/01/08/books/review/would-it-kill-you-to-stop-doing-that-a-modern-guide-to-manners-by-henry-alford-book-review.html |title=Henry Alford on How to Behave |author=Jincy Willet |date=6 January 2012 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=15 April 2012}}</ref>
==Reception== Jincy Willet of ''The New York Times'' said that the book "amuses as much as it informs". Sarah Halzack of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' called the book "a bit haphazard" although "his self-effacing tone and dry sense of humor help to unify the pieces".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/2012/01/09/gIQAXQFrnQ_story.html |title=‘Would It Kill You To Stop Doing That?: A Modern Guide to Manners’ by Henry Alford |author=Sarah Halzack |date=3 February 2012 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |accessdate=April 15, 2012}}</ref> Philip Marchand of ''[[National Post]]'' said that "sometimes his humour is a bit strained" although his advice can be "very practical".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://arts.nationalpost.com/2012/01/20/open-book-would-it-kill-you-to-stop-doing-that-by-henry-alford/ |title=Open Book: Would It Kill You to Stop Doing That? by Henry Alford |author=Philip Marchand |date=20 January 2012 |work=[[National Post]] |accessdate=15 April 2012}}</ref>
